    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-10-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-10-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.<gloss target="#t_BC1">BC</gloss>
                    Armaments/10–748: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>, in Paris</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">urgent</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-10-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 7, 1948—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss> 147. Dept has reservations re del
                    decision Oct. 1, on handling Soviet disarmament proposal as reported <gloss
                        target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 187, Oct. 2, 9 a. m.,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d245fn1">
                        <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 187, not printed, reported the
                        decisions taken by the Delegation at its 10th Meeting, October 1; for the
                        pertinent portion of the Minutes of that meeting, see <ref target="#pg_443"
                            >p. 443</ref>.</note> and desires consult Secretary on his return here
                    Oct. 9. Accordingly you should endeavor not to participate in disarmament debate
                    in Committee <pb facs="0471" n="451" xml:id="pg_451"/> 1 pending further
                    instructions. For your most secret info Dept wonders whether from propaganda
                    point of view some more affirmative response to Soviet proposals might not be
                    made.</p>
                <p>In view of fact that tomorrow will be devoted to plenary session we are hopeful
                    that our non-participation in debate can be contrived inconspiciously.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
